Hello everyone! I thought I'd do a little intro and even though most of y'all know a little about me already I'd like to tell you morrrre.My husband, Mark and I own 2 personal training gyms...one in Troy, MI and now we're expanding to Land O Lakes, FL near Tampa. 

I am a 41 yeats young mama of 3. Fitness has been a part of my life since 2000. I was introduced to weights and the gym by husband. I had always been a skinny weak unathletic self conscious teenager and lifting weights brought out my inner bad as beast. I was leaving my gym sessions feeling like I had never felt in my life. The more I lifted, the stronger and more confident I became in more ways than one. Weight lifting changed my life, my mood, my self concept, my outlook on life and as an added bonus gave my skinny scrawny body shape. I am forever grateful for this lifestyle and am excited to lead more women into it at our new studio in Florida beginning June 2021. When your dieting youâ€™ll inevitably get to a stage where your weight will stay the same or you wonâ€™t be losing as much as youâ€™d want...

This is completely normal and should be expected!

But what do you do when this happens?

First of all wait a week or 2 before making any drastic changes, your weight and body fat might keep dropping, as we all know weight can fluctuate a fair bit from day to day

If 1 or 2 weeks go by and thereâ€™s no change to weight or noticeable body change, you have 2 options to keep the progress moving

1ï¸âƒ£ Increase energy output 

Basically burn more calories in the day, this can be done by upping your step count, adding cardio in, increasing cardio and generally just being more active in the day

2ï¸âƒ£ Decrease energy input

By this I mean lower your calorie consumption, if you are tracking calories then lower your daily calories by 100-200, nothing crazy but enough to get the scales moving again

If your not tracking calories then you can do this by lowing portion sizes, less snacking, eating less calorific foods which are high in volume to keep you full, and upping protein intake

But generally just eating less!!

Adapting is apart of dieting!

When it comes to lifting heavy, Iâ€™m a big believer in creating your OWN weightlifting belt. Not an actual belt, Iâ€™m talking INTRA-ABDOMINAL PRESSURE. 

However, a belt definitely enhances your ability to stabilize the spine, so long as you maintain constant tension in the abdominal cavity! ğŸ’ª

Then why use a belt? ğŸ¤” 
For starters, a belt is the perfect tool to reinforce the muscles of the trunk. Secondly, it protects the low back...spine safety is always the top priority, ESPECIALLY when testing your maximal strength..By no means will I sacrifice my health to tell people I lifted â€œXâ€ amount of weight but walk with a limp for months on end.

How do we use one PROPERLY? ğŸ‹ï¸â€â™€ï¸ 
As stated above, we must learn to breathe and brace before we even think about starting our lifts. A big breath through the mouth (Belly breath) will expand the diaphragm downward, thus, creating pressure within our intra-abdominal cavity. 

Researchers have shown that athletes who wear a belt correctly tend to lift heavier weights with more explosive power. They are also able to maintain their trunk stiffness for more reps during higher rep maximum lifts like an 8 RM attempt ğŸ”¥ 

Warning âš ï¸ 
Repetitive use of a belt will cause the body to rely on the support of the belt. Which will begin  weaken the core it uses the belt as a crutch more than a tool to increase performance.

Why are some people reaching their goals, and some people not?

-

Everyone that goes to the gym has a goal in one way or another, whether thatâ€™s losing weight, getting stronger, getting fitter etc, but realistically how many people are actually arsed about achieving that goal? I genuinely mean it, I see so many people go in and just doss about on phones or just stand chatting constantly expecting the weight to just fall off, or the body to just grow. So much so that sometimes when you see someone attempt a huge lift, work to true failure, or even just be absolutely soaked after a session, they almost seem like the odd ones out.

-

For me personally, I know that each time I go in, I know exactly what numbers I need to hit, and I give 100% in order to do that, and to be honest, the results donâ€™t lie. My strength has increased massively, my body has changed massively, and my overall mindset has also changed massively over the course of this last training block. I genuinely have stopped caring what people think when Iâ€™m in there now, if I want to film something to get feedback? Sound Iâ€™ll do that. If I want to shout at myself to get a bit more hyped for my topsets? Sound Iâ€™ll do that. 

-

This isnâ€™t meant to come across by any means as an arrogant post, but more of a demonstration and example of what you can achieve when you fully put both your mind and effort to something. I am pretty new to bodybuilding since making the switch, but I will hit my goals regardless, and if that means being humbled by being told to knock the weight down/ improve form, or have to ask others who are more experienced for advice, then Iâ€™m going to do that.

-

At the end of the day, the one thing I love about training, is you get out of it exactly what you put in. All the effort you put in is reflected in the outcome of your training as a whole. So therefore, if youâ€™re only putting in 30%, donâ€™t expect 100% back.

caption:
Quick hour back session blasted out after work. A lot of focus on Lats here ğŸ’ªğŸ¼ 

*Lats - Latissimus Dorsi*

Exercise 1 - Single lat pulldown. Sit with the back straight and feel the stretch. Tuck your elbow into your side at the bottom and squeeze the lat. start light and work up. 1 set of 15 reps of light weight. 1 set of 12 reps moderate weight. 1 set of 10 reps heavy. 

Exercise 2 - Bent over rows. Excuse my fat hole in the video. Bend the knees with feet shoulder width apart and keep the back straight. Maintain good posture, lift as if strings are behind you pulling your elbows back. (If lifting heavy remember to wear a belt). Bar - 1x15reps. 40kg - 1x12-15reps. 60kg - 1x10-12reps. 

Exercise 3 - Rotary lat pull. This gives the back an amazing stretch. Keep tempo slow and controlled and tuck elbows into your hips at the bottom of the lift and squeeze the lats. 3 sets of a weight your comfortable with. If able to up it, even better. 

Exercise 4 - Lat pulldown. Keep slow and controlled. Donâ€™t sit directly straight, arch the back a little and pull the bar into your chest. This gives your back a better squeeze, when going back up, really feel the stretch. 1 set of 15 - light to moderate weight. 1 set of 12 moderate to heavy weight. 1 set of 10 heavy weight. 

Exercise 5 - To finish. Single arm bent over rows. Find a bench and lift the weight. Keep elbow at around 90Â° and tuck into your hip at the peak. Donâ€™t try to pull the dumbbells past your hip/back as this is over-extension and will cause back pain and injury. I used the same 20kg dumbbell for all 3 sets but if youâ€™re able to go heavier in your 2/3rd set, do!

Also remember, using a weight your comfortable with is good but the real progress is upping the weight. You probably wonâ€™t get the same amount of reps/sets with the heavier weight to start with but over time youâ€™ll get stronger and be more able to lift more. This is called progressive overload. As long as your form stays good, it will come. Enjoy ğŸ‘ğŸ¼

You know what that means? Another Hawai'i related topic! Mahalo nui (thank you very much) to everyone who responded to my story question on Hawai'i topics <3 
.
Today I'm telling you why I'm proud to be Native Hawaiian, which I'm 100% proud to be. NOTE: Being Native Hawaiian is an ethnicity and not everyone who lives in/grew up in Hawai'i is Hawaiian.
.
I'm proud for SO many reasons, but I'm primarily proud to be Hawaiian because of what this culture & it's people represent currently and have represented in the past. Hawaiians aren't perfect, and we can not all be put in the same box - but one thing I think we all are is resilient.
.
If you look at the history of Hawaiians - our form of dance & storytelling (hula) was banned (in 1830 considered a Pagan ritual), Hawaiian Kingdom was overthrown (1893) and Hawaiian language was banned (1896.) It wasn't until the 1980s (forty-ish years ago) that Hawaiian Language was formally taught again. We were considered â€œsavagesâ€ too. Today we are even at higher risk for smoking, alcoholism, and obesity with less access to healthcare. Iâ€™m lucky to be part of the 7.4% of Hawaiians with a professional education & degree. 
.
AND YET WE STILL HAVE OUR PEOPLE, TRADITIONS, CULTURE, AND LANGUAGE EXISTING TODAY. We, as a people, are still fighting for our land, sovereignty and so much more, but the fact that we still exist and I am here today as a healthy educated kanaka screams resilient to me. 
.

One meal isnâ€™t going to throw you off track but feeling guilty and adopting the fuck it attitude will.â â 
â â 
When youâ€™re tracking your food, eating healthily and seeing results, it can be frustrating if you feel like youâ€™ve â€œmessed up.â€â â 
â â 
One of the most important things is realising that a meal or a few drinks every now and then isnâ€™t going to mess up your progress or undo all of the work youâ€™ve put in. Enjoying and embracing it will only increase dietary adherence in most cases.â â 
â â 
However, the issue comes when you press the â€œfuck itâ€ button. When you think that one untracked meal has ruined your day, weekend or week. So you keep going because â€œyouâ€™ve ruined it so you may as well enjoy itâ€â â 
â â 
And over the next few days you notice your weight and measurements increasing, and your suspicion is confirmed - that meal out on Friday messed you up.â â 
â â 
But it wasnâ€™t that one meal. More often than not, youâ€™re probably still within your weekly calorie goal, especially if youâ€™re at maintenance or above.â â 
â â 
Even when youâ€™re in a deficit, what really matters is your weekly average. So even if you were a bit higher on one day, chances are itâ€™ll even out.â â 
â â 
It takes a lot of extra calories to push you out of a weekly deficit and into a surplus.â â 
â â 
Will one doughnut do it? Nah.â â 
â â 
Will one main course do it? Nah.â â 
â â 
Will letting an enjoyable meal turn into a binge because you feel guilty ruin your progress? Yeah maybe. â â 
â â 
Feeling guilty and promising youâ€™ll start again on Monday can make a meal turn into a main course with a side of chips, a milkshake, a bottle of wine, a dessert and a share size bag of sweets, followed by a takeaway the next day.â â 
â â 
Donâ€™t get stuck into an all or nothing attitude. Think of your effort and adherence like a thermostat. Dial it up high when you can, and at times if you need to turn it down a little bit, then do. But donâ€™t turn it off completely either.â â 
â â 
Learn how to enjoy the meals and foods you love. Because 9 times outta 10, itâ€™s not the food thatâ€™s stalking your progress, itâ€™s the feelings of guilt that lead to a fuck it attitude and a binge that is.â â 
â â

This is beneficial because it gives me something to look forward too, however I find I have created the perfect situation in my head and spent so long thinking about it that when it comes to the actual day, it is disappointing

I think this is self sabotaging as I set myself up for failure, for example if Iâ€™ve imagined I was going to have the nicest meal ever and then I donâ€™t, I think that it was not as good as it was supposed to be but in fact it was actually what was always going to happen I just imagined my own scenario

I always try to be positive so I usually imagine things to turn out so well but this isnâ€™t always the case

I would love to know your opinions on this topic and if anyone feels the same

A lifting belt is a piece of equipment designed to increase â€œintra-abdominal pressureâ€. 
 
Intra- meaning inside
Abdominal- meaning your abdomen
And pressure...is pressure.

So we are increasing the pressure inside our abdomen. 
This increased intra-abdominal pressure makes our trunk more rigid, allowing for more stability when we lift, in turn resulting in a small increase in performance when it comes to resistance training. 

On top of that, a lifting belt can sometimes decrease someoneâ€™s levels of pain while lifting especially with low back pain.

Do you always feel hungry but not sure why or how to make the feeling go away without just eating! 

Here is my top 5 tips 
- Drink more water, it has the potential to reduce your appetite when you consume your meals. Feelings of thirst can be mistaken for hunger.
- Eat more protein, as it has hunger reducing properties that will help you automatically consume less calories throughout the day.
- Nutritious meals, having meals with a healthy balance of Macros helps you stay fuller for longer. Processed foods can actually make your feel hungry after eating them
- Get enough sleep, studies have shown too little sleep can increase hunger by 24%
- Are you actually eating enough? Having too little calories will obviously make you hungry. Being on a calorie deficit means getting the balance right

Real talk, who doesn't want bigger arms?ğŸ˜…

The answer is simple, we all do. Having muscular arms demands respect, it's a very masculine look that we all desire.

A big, strong upper body has always been the goal for any fitness enthusiast. 

From a wide chest to a pair of round shoulders, these muscles make the physique and having abs is definitely a plus..

But how often are we walking around with our shirts off?ğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™‚ï¸

When you're building your body, you need to be practical, and strength comes from the arms. So let's dive into the basics of building bigger arms.

The solution? Moving away from the basics and focusing on a few key advanced concepts, you can add slabs of muscle to your arms and start splitting your sleeves in no time.

âœ…Technique 1: Progressive overload

With progressive overload, youâ€™ll continually lift more to make your muscles work harder than theyâ€™re accustomed to. 

This excess demand will help you to make gains in muscle size, strength and endurance.

Here are three ways you can progressively overload your muscles.

1. Increase resistance â€“ Add more weight

2. Increase sets â€“ add a couple more sets to each exercise

3. Increase reps- mix up your volume with higher and lower rep schemes. 

âœ…Technique 2: Time under tension (TUT)

Time under tension simply refers to how long a specific muscle group is under strain during a set. 

You can probably do 10 reps of barbell bicep curls in about 15-20 seconds. 

But simply by doing them more slowly, you can increase that time under tension to 35-40 seconds. 

This forces your biceps to work 15-20 seconds longer allowing the muscle fibers to grow.

By combining progresive overload and tempo training with a sound bicep and tricep program, your muscles will have no choice but to grow. ğŸ”¥

WHAT TO KEEP IN MIND WHEN TRYING TO GET ABS:
I get a load of people come and ask me for abs workouts telling me all they want is to get abs. The reality is, the only way you can get abs is by losing fat by eating in a calorie deficit. Especially for those of you trying to bulk up, getting abs (and being in a calorie deficit) is just going to make it harder to gain muscle. Training abs everyday will not get you abs, you have to be at a low enough body fat to see them. If you are trying to gain muscle you are far better off lean bulking then cutting back any fat you have gained and any you had to start with. Dropping fat before you start going to the gym will not get you a ripped physique.

Obviously if you have a lot of fat to begin with you can lose fat and gain muscle (body recomposition), eating in a calorie deficit where your body will burn the fat to make up the excess calories to build however for the majority this is going to be inefficient and make it harder for you to reach your goals.

You have to also remember that as with the rest of â€˜bodybuildingâ€™ or with any sport a lot of it is down to genetics, some people will have far better/or worse insertions and metabolisms which will make it easier or harder to get abs respectively.

There is no â€˜quick fixâ€™ to getting abs so bear that in mind when working towards whatever your goals are, whether you bulk or cut doing either excessively will not be beneficial and will leave you worse off than where you are now. 

Keep working hard and you will get there.

caption:
What brings you absolute joy?
.
In case you hadn't noticed, for me, it's bright colourful gymwear, the ability and opportunity to train hard and FOOOD!
.
I feel that exercise and eating should bring you joy. Maybe not EVERY SINGLE DAY but for a good 90% of your week it's important to enjoy the journey and the process. 
.
Have a training plan and include exercises that are both going to help you reach your goals AND you those you enjoy doing. 
.
When it comes to nutrition not all plans work for all. Counting calories, macros, portions sizes, fasting, intermittent fasting, intuative eating --- each one has it's pro's and con's so make sure you choose the right one for you again to help you with goals AND ensure you aren't miserable.
.
I've found my happy balance, loving training, great nutrition plan and a big part of that comes from my coach but also knowing what works for me, what makes me happy and what I want out of my training and nutrition.
.
In a nutshell you do you. Don't just follow what your friend is doing, take time to look at where you want to be and what you're willing to sacrifice. 
.

When I first created this account, I was SO worried about what other people would think. Although I was comfortable in myself & within the gym, I was worried that people would think I was a try hard/wonder who I thought I was for posting about my gym progress ğŸ˜‚ 

If you know me youâ€™ll know I hate being the centre of attention, so me making a page literally dedicated to my fitness was a big dealğŸ˜‚ I took a step out my comfort zone making this account, because I wanted to make other people feel more comfortable. 

I know first hand (even still now!) how uncomfortable women can feel in the gym. Weâ€™re stared at, followed around, inappropriate questions asked (someone asked me how much I weighed ğŸ™ƒ). Why is it STILL that some people see women as being aliens in the gym?ğŸ˜‚ 

My â€œaudienceâ€ (hate that word lol) is primarily women aged around 18-24, so my sort of age, and the age Iâ€™d imagine itâ€™s most common to feel uncomfortable in the gym. Donâ€™t get me wrong, I do not feel 100% comfortable all of the time - but Iâ€™ve learned that thatâ€™s not a reflection on me, but on other peopleâ€™s weird behaviourğŸ˜‚ 

Soooo, here are the things I do/have done to make myself feel more comfortable in the gym â¤ï¸ 

1ï¸âƒ£wear an outfit you love/feel good in - honestly think this is so underrated & I know for me anyway it can massively affect my workout ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜­

2ï¸âƒ£ make friends!! I know this isnâ€™t easy, and Iâ€™ve been lucky in the sense my boyfriend works at my gym, but having friends that I know will keep an eye out for me if someone makes me uncomfortable has been realllly nice 

3ï¸âƒ£ MUSIC!!!!!! I know we probably all will listen to music whilst training, but having a good playlist that you genuinely enjoy, so youâ€™re not having to skip songs all the time is a game changer lol 

4ï¸âƒ£ take some time getting used to the exercises youâ€™re doing. idk about anyone else but I used to get so paranoid Iâ€™d be doing things wrong and people would laugh, which would prevent me from doing them at all. YouTube is your friend - the amount of times Iâ€™ve looked up tutorials of how to do stuff/set things up is a joke hahaha 

5ï¸âƒ£ remember you have just as much right to be there as anybody else ğŸ’˜

If you are past the beginnerâ€™s stage and want to gain muscle, one of the best body part splits you can use to accomplish this is the push/pull/legs split routine.â£
-
The essence of push/pull(legs is that you split your body into three body parts, where each body part is trained on its own separate day. On your push day you train chest, shoulders and triceps. In the pull workout you train the back and biceps. Lastly, on the leg day you train your quads, hamstring and calfs. Some people also train abdominals on leg day. â£
-
With push/pull/legs you train all related muscle groups together. This means that you get the maximum overlap of movements within the same workout, and the muscle groups being trained get an overall benefit from this overlap.â£
-
For example when you train chest with say bench press, you are also hitting your anterior deltoids and triceps hard. And when you train shoulders you are again involving your triceps. So it makes sense to work these all together in the same workout for maximum synergy and effectiveness.â£
-
Similarly when you train your back your biceps are heavily involved, so it again makes sense to train these immediately afterwards so that they can derive the maximum benefit from the additional stimulation.â£

Supplement Dictionary: Vitamin C

In my opinion Vitamin C is the most underrated supplement you can take in modern bodybuilding. Everybody is talking about all kind of supplements and their positive impact on your body and recovery, but somehow not many people see the advantages Vitamin C can have, especially in quite high dosages, when training hard and with high intensity. What are the biggest benefits in using L-Ascorbic Acid? Letâ€™s check it out. 

Boost for your immune system 

Vitamin C has great benefits on your immune system and helps to shorten the time you have common colds. 

A very potent antioxidant 

Vitamin C helps to reduce cellular damages caused by so called free radicals. Doing this at the same time it reduces inflammations and cell damage in your body and thus help you to recover faster. Vitamin C also helps you to boost the production of the protein collagen which is good for wound healing, keeps your skin supple and youthful, and helps maintaining a healthy cartilage and bones. 

Helps to reduce the risk of a heart attack

Vitamin C helps to prevent negative blood-vesselÂ changes, plaque buildup, and Â hardening of the arteries that canÂ lead to strokes, heart attacks, andÂ other vascular diseases. Also helpsÂ maintaining healthy arteries and arterialÂ walls. This is very important, asÂ the arterial lining is what pumps outÂ nitric oxide and is essential for heartÂ health, healthy blood flow, andÂ optimal blood pressure. 

Reduces stress and cortisol levels

Itâ€™s highly important for bodybuilders to try to keep their stress and cortisol levels as low as possible to stay out of catabolism. But every hard training increases these levels and a high doses If Vitamin C are proven to be very effective in reducing cortisol and stress levels. By doing this you help your body to be more in an anabolic state and thus build up more muscle mass. 

You see that Vitamin C has a lot of highly interesting benefits especially for anybody whoâ€™s into bodybuilding and wants to get the maximum out of it.

Una variaciÃ³n en un ejercicio es cuando el ejercicio tradicional lo trabajamos de una manera diferente. Puede resultar ser mÃ¡s fÃ¡cil, complicado y/o retante. 

Aqui les dejo 2 variaciones de los ejercicios Latpulldown y Dumbbell Row

1. Incline Wide Grip Latpulldown: muchas personas trabajan este ejercicio de manera incorrecta en su postura natural (ejercicio tradicional). Al utilizar el banco levemente inclinado, obligamos al pecho a mantener contacto con el banco (pecho grande), se evita el famoso â€œswingâ€ del ejercicio (manera incorrecta) y el ejercicio es mÃ¡s efectivo enfocÃ¡ndose en los dorsales anchos (latissimus dorsi) la parte mÃ¡s ancha de la espalda.

2. Double Arm Dumbbell Row: normalmente, este ejercicio se trabaja con una mano mientras la otra mano hace contacto con banco, rodilla o rack para mantener estabilidad y postura. Esta variaciÃ³n es un poco compleja ya que utilizas ambas manos para la ejecuciÃ³n del ejercicio. Debes mantener la postura de la espalda erguida e inclinada hacia alfrente (pecho grande). Lo complejo de este ejercicio es que utilizas otros grupos musculares que sirven como estabilizadores para mantener la postura correcta. Si no tienes estos grupos musculares fortalecidos, la postura del ejercicio se verÃ¡ afectada y por ende, puedes causarte una lesiÃ³n.

âŒ 'BAD' FOOD MYTH BUSTER âŒâ£
â£
THERE IS NO SUCH THING AS A BAD FOOD.â£
â£
We live in a time where our diet culture is to make you feel ashamed about how you eat, and what foods you put in your body. â£
Demonising foods, or a specific food group, most commonly carbs at present, can have detrimental results on our mental, and emotional health. It can make us feel bad for eating it, feel bad for wanting to eat it and can lead us to punishing ourselves for enjoying the food we actually like! â£
We become restrictive, and have to withstand the pressure and stress  of basing our day and social events around food. â£
â£
ğŸ”¥YOUR BODY NEEDS FUEL TO FUNCTIONğŸ”¥â£
â£
A diet doesn't need to be 100% "healthy" to be healthy. â£
If we become less restrictive through our day-to-day, we can reduce the changes of binging, and overindulging during a low or hormonal day/ weekend. â£
â£
Use the 80/20 rule. â£
â£
80% of your daily calorie intake should consist of quality, nutrient rich foods. â£
-Whole grainsâ£
-Fruits and vegetablesâ£
-Lean proteinâ£
-Unsaturated fats from avocados or olive oilâ£
â£
Whilst, â£
â£
20% should consist of your treats. The food you crave and can't live without. â£
ENJOY IT, and get rid of that feeling of guilt. â£
â£
TIP â£
Save your treat for the afternoon/ evening. â£
Have something to look forward to! â£
â£

Letâ€™s chat habitsğŸŒ¸ 

Something I miss about being on prep is that it was a strict lifestyle with a lot of things that became habits for me- when the show got postponed I felt a sense of loss. Although I fell off the bandwagon a bit of sticking to my routine the habits that were created stuck. 

Some of those habits are 
1. Moving my body daily (strength training, running stairs, walking, stretching etc) 
2. Starting my day early. For me personally, I was able to accomplish more when I got up earlier compared to how I used to stay up really late and be rushed in the morning. 
3. Preparing my items for the next day the night before. Since I get up early, Iâ€™m also that person who will stay in bed until my 4th alarm goes off (oops) so I have found that prepping my breakfast, my workout gear, my work supplies etc the night before has become a habit that truly has made my mornings more seamless which has also helped with managing some of my anxiety. 

Personally I find that less is more when it comes to habits, when I want to form a new one I slowly incorporate it into my life so that it is more likely to stick. 

Happy FriYAY everyone, have a good weekend and get outside ğŸŒ¸â˜€ï¸

âœ…INTRODUCTION

ğŸ“Pulmonary embolism (PE) is a blockage of one of the pulmonary arteries in the lungs. In most cases, a deep venous thrombosis (DVT) forms in the leg. Once dislodged, the thrombus travels to the lungs where it occludes the pulmonary artery. The condition is a medical emergency that requires prompt diagnosis and treatment to ensure patient survival.

âœ…PATHOLOGICAL PROCESS

ğŸ“Thrombus formation occurs due to stasis in the deep veins, especially at the calf. The patient's initial cardiorespiratory status, and size and number of emboli affects the severity of changes in pulmonary blood flow and respiration. A small blockage of the pulmonary artery may not provoke symptoms, while a large embolus can be fatal.

ğŸ“In the latter case, pulmonary embolism causes wasted ventilation as it increases the alveoli dead space, resulting in a ventilation-perfusion mismatch and an increase in pulmonary artery pressures and right ventricular work.  Consequently, there is eventual right heart failure, followed by the left side of the heart due to decrease in blood volume and coronary perfusion to the left ventricle. Cardiac muscle dysfunction ensues, and the heart ceases to pump blood.

âœ…PHYSIOTHERAPY IMPLICATIONS

ğŸ“Mobility is vital to patient recovery following PE. Following anticoagulation and thrombolytic therapies, bed rest is typically prescribed followed by inpatient therapy. The main aim of physiotherapy is to restore a clear lung field and oxygen uptake to optimal level. This may be achieved through chest physiotherapy and then progressed to include endurance exercises such as walking or bicycle ergometry.

WHY YOU SHOULDN'T BE FOLLOWING LOW CALORIE DIETS

although a lot of people know that eating in a calorie deficit is the only way to lose fat, a lot still think that the lower calories they eat = the better.

HOWEVER, PLEASE REMEMBER: FOOD ISN'T SOMETHING YOU NEED TO 'BURN OFF'. YOUR BODY NEEDS FOOD TO FUNCTION. INTERNALLY, YOUR ORGANS ARE WORKING HARD TO KEEP YOU ALIVE, IT NEEDS CALORIES TO WORK. 

here are ways that LOW CALORIE DIET NEGATIVELY EFFECTS YOUR INTERNAL BODY FUNCTIONS: 
1. Reproductive Functions ğŸ¼ 
during a low calorie diet, the body cuts down production of sex hormones (testosterone, estrogen, progesterone and other androgens)
for women this can lead to:
â®• irregular or lost of menstrual cycles
â®• hormonal imbalance
â®• pre menopause symptomps or early menopause
it can lead to infertility for both men and women
2. Cognitive Functions ğŸ§  
the brain needs a lot of energy constantly, a low calorie diet can slow down brain metabolism which may result in
â®• being more forgetful
â®• brain fog
â®• less creative
3. Repair and Restoration ğŸ©¸ 
remember, our body's tissues are always being broken down and rebuilt/replenished inside our body.
thus, if people who exercise regularly (active individuals) don't eat enough, they won't recover properly
4. Vitamins and Minerals ğŸ¥’ 
due to a low energy intake, it's hard to reach all micronutrients such as vitamins and minerals- when in fact, we need them for a healthy metabolism.

Motivation doesnâ€™t come handed on a plate all the time. Sometimes you have to really talk to yourself and find the discipline to make yourself do things. Sometimes you wonâ€™t have any motivation and you wonâ€™t be able to talk yourself around. And sometimes you just have to put your comfort blanket on (or cardigan in my case) and go with the flow until you find yourself again. 

Itâ€™s finally Friday! Iâ€™ve had a strange week. Iâ€™ve really found my feet with all things fitness and nutrition and feel Iâ€™m in a good place with that side of things and itâ€™s feeling amazing. But Iâ€™ve really struggled to drag myself out of bed in the mornings and go for the walk, run or bike ride that I normally would before starting work. And Iâ€™ve felt so sluggish for not doing it and that feeling has genuinely lasted all day, but Iâ€™ve still had no motivation to do it the following day. Iâ€™ve really beat myself up for it, but we donâ€™t need to. Sometimes we do just need to look at all that we are achieving and not give ourselves a hard time for being a bit slack with something else at the same time. So now Iâ€™ve had a bit of a break, and Iâ€™m doing something wild here and starting afresh tomorrow. Yes on a Saturday, because we shouldnâ€™t just wait for Monday all the time or itâ€™ll never happen. 

Do what you need to do, whether thatâ€™s in the form of choosing to stay in bed an extra half hour because you appreciate a lie in and slow start to the day, or jumping up and out of bed at 5am and throwing yourself into your day. Do whatever makes you happy and gives you a sense of satisfaction but whatever it is, donâ€™t beat yourself up if itâ€™s not the option you â€˜shouldâ€™ be choosing. There is no right or wrong. Train For Your Mental HealthğŸ§  

With it being mental health awareness week I thought I share a little something about much I value training for mental health.

I would say there was a good 2-3 years where I was a little lost, as any young person may feel at that time in their life, but training was the one thing that honestly kept me going...

Knowing that I had that 1 hour a day to escape whatever else was going on & focus on myself for a bit was what I looked forward to everyday. Not to say there wasnâ€™t days where I didnâ€™t want to, trust me thereâ€™s plenty days, but itâ€™s that reminder of how good you feel after you get past that little bit of suffering. And getting through one bit of suffering, will help you to surpass the next battle you may face.

Once you learn & understand the value of training, not just for your physical health, but also mental, then youâ€™ll start to see other aspects of you life come together as well.

Training (and I mean proper training, not just doing an incline walk on the treadmill for 20 minutes) will teach you so many lessons:
* Resilience
* Discipline
* Consistency
* Humility
* Tolerance Of Physical & Mental Pain

These days, I like to finish my workouts with something for the mind. So to that dark place & come out of it feeling that sense of euphoria knowing what you have just accomplished.

For Time:
50 Cal Assault Bike
50 KB Swings
50 Air Squats
100 Butterfly Sit Ups
50 Air Squats
50 KB Swings
50 Cal Assault Bike

Simple but a test. (Especially after a squat session...)

Youâ€™ll learn about yourself the more you do sh*t like this that hurts you. But youâ€™ll also be a lot strong for it.

So if youâ€™re someone who is struggling in any way at all, I urge you to train. Whatever your capabilities, just do something that is going to be tough. Push yourself through it & see what type of person comes out of it at the end.

Itâ€™s more than just training,
Itâ€™s more than just looking good,
Itâ€™s a life changer,
And sometimes a life saver.

E M O T I O N

Is energy in motion, meaning this current emotion you're feeling is not meant to stay with you forever. 

You may have heard the saying, "This too shall pass." 

As a human being you have the wonderful experiences of being content, happiness, and the down right painful experience of emotions. It can make or break us depending on how you have learned to cope with them.

Emotions..
Trigger us
Motivate us
Mold us
And shape us into who we are.

Finding healthy ways to deal with them are one of the biggest gifts you could ever give yourself.

Taking time to acknowledge how you feel in the present moment and being grateful for each and every feeling that passes through you.

I used to be the great represser of emotion because I thought I had to be a certain way. I allowed what I thought other people would think of me to effect the way I reacted to situations. Instead of honoring myself and following through with what I really wanted I lowered my frequency to match someone else's. I avoided confrontation and in return was sabatoging myself and the relationships around me.

I was the person who made sure everyone else was happy except one big issue, I was going against everything my soul really aligned with.

In doing this I lost my grip on life. I would drown out how I felt and numb the built up pain I had been hoarding, all so I seemed a certain way.

It exhausting but you can learn another way.

So I began my healing journey âœ¨

Lower back issues affect many adults over the course of a lifetime so they should be addressed as early as possible.â 
This weakness can lead to injuries in other parts of the body, most notably the hamstring or quad. â 
The sad part is that the causes of back injury can be reduced or even prevented. â 
Tips to prevent back pain:â 
1. Stretch and mobilise the hip flexors daily.â 
2. Regularly train hip external rotation, glutei medius along with regular glutei Maximus exercises such as RDL and single leg RDL. â 
3. Do planks and side planks, working on moving the extremities while preventing any movement of the spine. â 
4. Ab crunches can actually increase stress through the lower back depending on the person, so be careful which abdominal exercise you use. â 
5. Perform superman isometric holds and progress to horizontal back extension isometric holds with weight. â

Sorry dames en heren, maar er zijn geen oefeningen dat direct buikvet wegwerkt.

Als je mij al een tijdje volgt, dan weet je dit vast wel al. Wellicht heb je het ook al geprobeerd. 

Je hebt een kcal onderschot nodig om vet te verliezen, dit is de waarheid en een feit, we noemen dit thermodynamica, dit is een natuurwet en kan je niet omheen, net zoals dat zwaartekracht een feit is. 

Dat wilt nog niet zeggen dat het allemaal zo makkelijk is. Met alle luxe en overvolle supermarkten die we tegenwoordig hebben en alle lekkere dingen en wie vind een macdonalds, kfc of een dikke pizza nou niet soms lekker. 

Ik begrijp het, toch wil het niet zeggen dat je al die dingen moet weglaten om je doelen te behalen. 

Ik focus met mijn klanten op al die factoren zodat je nog altijd kan genieten van je leven zonder dat je alles hoeft op te geven.

ğŸ–¤ Unilateral exercises ğŸ–¤

Unilateral exercises are single side, such as lunges or split squats. You have only one side (or limb) working at a time. And they are super good to have in your program!

Theyâ€™re a great way at identifying and fixing imbalances, and also use a lot more stabilising muscles than a bilateral movement such as a normal squat does. These tend to be muscles we donâ€™t train in isolation so unilateral is a great way to hit them ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥

Theyâ€™re also very useful for muscle isolation such as a single arm bicep curl, all your attention is focused on that muscle and movement. This can increase the mind muscle connection which is needed for muscle growth. 

In addition to only moving one side you can unilaterally load your exercises (only hold weight on one side, either the working side or the opposite) which also focuses on your stability and core. 

The downside is they take longer as each set is double the time â±
